00:00:27.266 --> 00:00:30.850
ROBERT TOWNSEND: That's
the starting point,

00:00:30.850 --> 00:00:35.500
but we're going to then move,
in the latter half of the class,

00:00:35.500 --> 00:00:38.290
to what to make of it, what
happens if you find that it's

00:00:38.290 --> 00:00:41.110
complete or incomplete,
how to think

00:00:41.110 --> 00:00:46.980
about policy through
the lens of this model,

00:00:46.980 --> 00:00:51.310
how to design insurance
instruments, what damage they

00:00:51.310 --> 00:00:54.790
actually might do, what the
distribution of benefits

00:00:54.790 --> 00:00:56.320
might be.

00:00:56.320 --> 00:00:58.420
There is a recurring
theme today,

00:00:58.420 --> 00:01:01.750
which wouldn't surprise
you, knowing me, which

00:01:01.750 --> 00:01:09.050
is theory is guiding
the whole discussion,

00:01:09.050 --> 00:01:13.730
rather than starting with
some randomized control trial

00:01:13.730 --> 00:01:16.850
and targeting, but we
will get to those control

00:01:16.850 --> 00:01:18.410
trials in the discussion.

00:01:20.960 --> 00:01:22.150
OK.

00:01:22.150 --> 00:01:23.260
So here's the outline.

00:01:27.550 --> 00:01:29.500
We'll look at risk and
insurance and village

00:01:29.500 --> 00:01:32.650
India, move to a
benchmark way of measuring

00:01:32.650 --> 00:01:36.700
the effectiveness of
financial institutions

00:01:36.700 --> 00:01:38.070
on the formal side.

00:01:38.070 --> 00:01:41.380
We'll then couple that with
work on the informal side

00:01:41.380 --> 00:01:46.060
and networks and so on.

00:01:46.060 --> 00:01:47.080
We'll get to this--

00:01:47.080 --> 00:01:49.540
can well-intended
interventions actually

00:01:49.540 --> 00:01:53.740
result in well welfare losses?

00:01:53.740 --> 00:02:01.300
And then issues of why insurance
take up in many circumstances

00:02:01.300 --> 00:02:02.710
is actually quite low.

00:02:16.320 --> 00:02:18.750
The idea here is that
people in village India,

00:02:18.750 --> 00:02:20.700
and developing economies
more generally,

00:02:20.700 --> 00:02:24.900
live in very high-risk
environments.

00:02:24.900 --> 00:02:27.510
There are ways to
cope with this risk--

00:02:27.510 --> 00:02:29.990
ex-ante and ex-post.

00:02:29.990 --> 00:02:35.010
Ex-ante, you can diversify
your crops, fields, activities,

00:02:35.010 --> 00:02:37.950
and occupations.

00:02:37.950 --> 00:02:43.905
Ex-post, you can have financial
transactions, gifts, loans.

00:02:43.905 --> 00:02:46.680
I actually mentioned
this the first lecture.

00:02:50.670 --> 00:02:53.610
How well are households doing?

00:02:53.610 --> 00:02:59.130
So the idea in this
paper is forget

00:02:59.130 --> 00:03:00.900
enumerating all the mechanisms.

00:03:00.900 --> 00:03:03.750
You're likely to miss one
anyway and the measurement

00:03:03.750 --> 00:03:04.920
might be really bad.

00:03:04.920 --> 00:03:07.080
Let's just look at the outcomes.

00:03:07.080 --> 00:03:11.700
The null hypothesis-- If
risk sharing were perfect,

00:03:11.700 --> 00:03:18.210
what would you expect to see
in consumption and income data?

00:03:18.210 --> 00:03:23.740
I think this style of work,
although nowadays it's

00:03:23.740 --> 00:03:27.370
not only accepted, it's highly
utilized all over the place,

00:03:27.370 --> 00:03:32.710
but initially there was a
confusion that perfect means

00:03:32.710 --> 00:03:35.590
complete as incomplete
markets, and somehow you're

00:03:35.590 --> 00:03:39.070
saying you're going to have all
these Arrow-Debreu securities

00:03:39.070 --> 00:03:41.350
being traded in a
village economy,

00:03:41.350 --> 00:03:44.560
and no, that's not the idea.

00:03:44.560 --> 00:03:49.270
Informal institutions can be
at work, as well as some spot

00:03:49.270 --> 00:03:50.920
market exchanges.

00:03:50.920 --> 00:03:52.930
You don't need to take
a stand on any of that

00:03:52.930 --> 00:03:54.805
if you're just going to
look at the outcomes.

00:03:58.440 --> 00:04:02.170
So the idea is
individual consumption

00:04:02.170 --> 00:04:07.210
should actually not depend on
individual income, stunningly.

00:04:10.030 --> 00:04:14.120
Once you control for
aggregate consumption,

00:04:14.120 --> 00:04:18.560
it's as if all these households
lived in a big risk syndicate,

00:04:18.560 --> 00:04:20.839
and they were just pooling
all their grain and so

00:04:20.839 --> 00:04:24.530
on in one big pile, and
then depending on shares,

00:04:24.530 --> 00:04:27.380
and some people are
more equal than others,

00:04:27.380 --> 00:04:31.540
they get a fraction
of the grain.

00:04:31.540 --> 00:04:35.840
A pile of the grain can go up
and down with village aggregate

00:04:35.840 --> 00:04:40.910
shocks, but controlling
for those shocks,

00:04:40.910 --> 00:04:44.390
your contribution has nothing
to do with what you take out.

00:04:51.610 --> 00:04:54.475
So where to test?

00:04:56.917 --> 00:04:58.750
We're going to do these
tests at the village

00:04:58.750 --> 00:05:04.500
level in this starting point of
this lecture, but we'll move.

00:05:04.500 --> 00:05:08.790
It could be kinship
networks within a village,

00:05:08.790 --> 00:05:10.200
family related people.

00:05:10.200 --> 00:05:12.450
It could be bigger than that.

00:05:12.450 --> 00:05:14.680
It could be a
cross-village risk sharing.

00:05:14.680 --> 00:05:18.480
It could be that being a member
of a financial institution,

00:05:18.480 --> 00:05:23.580
for example, is allowing
you to be part of a larger

00:05:23.580 --> 00:05:27.580
risk pooling population.

00:05:27.580 --> 00:05:30.330
So it's a judgment call
about where to apply it.

00:05:30.330 --> 00:05:33.930
Fortunately in the work
today, I can show you it

00:05:33.930 --> 00:05:37.470
being applied at various
distinct levels, which

00:05:37.470 --> 00:05:42.210
is a theme we'll come back
to next Thursday as well.

00:05:42.210 --> 00:05:43.700
Why did I choose villages?

00:05:43.700 --> 00:05:47.130
I had some idea that
everybody knows each other,

00:05:47.130 --> 00:05:50.580
and the environment
is relatively simple,

00:05:50.580 --> 00:05:54.620
and it just seemed like
the idealized setting.

00:05:54.620 --> 00:05:58.190
Of course, in practice not
all villages are alike,

00:05:58.190 --> 00:06:00.320
and they're pretty
complicated, and you've

00:06:00.320 --> 00:06:02.240
got people interacting
with one another,

00:06:02.240 --> 00:06:04.280
and they don't all
love each other.

00:06:07.090 --> 00:06:09.520
But that was the
motivation to begin with.

00:06:12.970 --> 00:06:17.180
By the way, if there's
no idiosyncratic risk

00:06:17.180 --> 00:06:23.900
there's nothing to test,
because the benchmark

00:06:23.900 --> 00:06:26.090
says controlling
for the aggregate is

00:06:26.090 --> 00:06:30.170
the idiosyncratic influencing
consumption or not.

00:06:30.170 --> 00:06:33.620
And if there's no idiosyncratic,
it's all aggregate,

00:06:33.620 --> 00:06:37.080
you can't do that test.

00:06:37.080 --> 00:06:39.880
This extends, of course,
beyond households

00:06:39.880 --> 00:06:43.900
within a village to tests
across villages and so on.

00:06:48.060 --> 00:06:51.500
Now, many people have the
idea that villages which

00:06:51.500 --> 00:06:55.910
they may never go
into are all alike,

00:06:55.910 --> 00:06:57.860
and it's all a function
of the rainfall,

00:06:57.860 --> 00:07:01.460
and it's all aggregate, and
that's just not true at all.

00:07:01.460 --> 00:07:07.880
And I'll show you the front end
of this paper, some statistics.

00:07:07.880 --> 00:07:10.130
Although it is true there
may be a lot of diversity

00:07:10.130 --> 00:07:13.580
in a village, if they all
completely diversified

00:07:13.580 --> 00:07:17.060
and did not specialize and they
all held a common portfolio,

00:07:17.060 --> 00:07:19.250
then, again, there
would be nothing

00:07:19.250 --> 00:07:24.130
to test as if they're doing it
all ex-ante and not ex-post,

00:07:24.130 --> 00:07:27.700
because the starting point would
be the income coming from all

00:07:27.700 --> 00:07:29.410
these diversified activities.

00:07:33.120 --> 00:07:34.530
But again, they don't do that.

00:07:43.250 --> 00:07:46.360
So let's take a look, these
so-called ICRISAT villages--

00:07:46.360 --> 00:07:49.090
Institute for Crops Research
in the Semi-Arid Tropic--

00:07:49.090 --> 00:07:52.990
at one point that was the source
of virtually the only panel

00:07:52.990 --> 00:08:00.030
data on developing
countries in the world.

00:08:00.030 --> 00:08:02.830
And it was gathered monthly,
and essentially for 10 years.

00:08:02.830 --> 00:08:05.860
They've started it up
again, interestingly.

00:08:05.860 --> 00:08:07.840
And there are other data
sets like that, where

00:08:07.840 --> 00:08:11.930
there are gaps of decades.

00:08:11.930 --> 00:08:15.670
So it's not true that
ICRISAT was the only source

00:08:15.670 --> 00:08:17.470
of panel variation.

00:08:17.470 --> 00:08:22.210
In Aurepalle, they're
growing castor and sorghum.

00:08:22.210 --> 00:08:25.120
Each crop is quite risky if
you look at the coefficient

00:08:25.120 --> 00:08:28.300
of variation.

00:08:28.300 --> 00:08:30.100
Those numbers are
comparable to something

00:08:30.100 --> 00:08:36.159
I did in medieval England,
where roughly every 12,

00:08:36.159 --> 00:08:40.080
13 years, they would
experience a famine.

00:08:40.080 --> 00:08:45.630
So these are high-risk
environments.

00:08:45.630 --> 00:08:50.320
Of course you could
diversify across these crops.

00:08:50.320 --> 00:08:51.730
That helps.

00:08:51.730 --> 00:08:54.520
Depending on the pair
of crops that you pick,

00:08:54.520 --> 00:08:57.910
the cross-crop correlations
could be as low as 0.09

00:08:57.910 --> 00:09:00.100
or something much higher.

00:09:00.100 --> 00:09:02.110
A low number is a good
thing, because you

00:09:02.110 --> 00:09:03.700
can spread your risk.

00:09:06.510 --> 00:09:09.420
Soil isn't uniform either.

00:09:09.420 --> 00:09:11.340
You can look, for a
given crop, at how

00:09:11.340 --> 00:09:16.990
the coefficient of variation
varies from one type of soil

00:09:16.990 --> 00:09:18.350
to another.

00:09:18.350 --> 00:09:21.580
And again, the cross-soil
correlation for a given crop

00:09:21.580 --> 00:09:25.780
is 0.37, and relatively low.

00:09:25.780 --> 00:09:27.880
Nevertheless, as I
said, it's not true

00:09:27.880 --> 00:09:31.120
that all households hold
a diversified basket

00:09:31.120 --> 00:09:32.540
of all these things.

00:09:32.540 --> 00:09:33.040
Yes.

00:09:33.040 --> 00:09:34.498
AUDIENCE: Are there any
crops that are negatively

00:09:34.498 --> 00:09:35.956
correlated with each other?

00:09:39.507 --> 00:09:41.090
ROBERT TOWNSEND: Not
in these numbers,

00:09:41.090 --> 00:09:43.190
although I certainly
wouldn't rule it out.

00:09:48.440 --> 00:09:50.750
Well, and some of those
numbers are point estimates,

00:09:50.750 --> 00:09:51.590
relatively low.

00:09:51.590 --> 00:09:55.935
And you put the standard
error bands, and yeah.

00:09:55.935 --> 00:09:56.920
OK.

00:09:56.920 --> 00:10:01.480
This is by cruder categories,
like labor income, income

00:10:01.480 --> 00:10:04.690
from trade and handicrafts,
animal husbandry.

00:10:04.690 --> 00:10:09.280
And it's stratified, as ICRISAT
did, by the amount of land

00:10:09.280 --> 00:10:10.240
that they hold--

00:10:10.240 --> 00:10:13.810
none, small, medium,
and large landholders.

00:10:13.810 --> 00:10:19.120
And these are sort of
basically fractions of income

00:10:19.120 --> 00:10:21.130
that they get from such things.

00:10:21.130 --> 00:10:26.710
Large landholders have the bulk
of their income from crops,

00:10:26.710 --> 00:10:29.860
and a substantial amount
from animal husbandry.

00:10:29.860 --> 00:10:33.910
People without land virtually
have no crop income.

00:10:33.910 --> 00:10:35.830
And the dominant
source is from labor.

00:10:35.830 --> 00:10:38.930
And there's everything
else in between,

00:10:38.930 --> 00:10:41.080
as you might anticipate.

00:10:41.080 --> 00:10:43.030
There were three
villages involved.

00:10:43.030 --> 00:10:46.480
That pattern is pretty common.

00:10:46.480 --> 00:10:49.270
And here, again, by
those income sources--

00:10:49.270 --> 00:10:50.860
(EXCITEDLY) hey, a
negative number--

00:10:54.790 --> 00:10:58.070
again, in the lower bound of
the stair of the confidence

00:10:58.070 --> 00:10:58.570
interval.

00:11:01.270 --> 00:11:04.180
Well, actually this is--

00:11:04.180 --> 00:11:08.980
even the point
estimates went negative.

00:11:08.980 --> 00:11:10.990
Sorry, no no.

00:11:10.990 --> 00:11:12.040
Yes, yes.

00:11:12.040 --> 00:11:15.880
This is hard to read because
these items should also

00:11:15.880 --> 00:11:18.020
be listed on the rows.

00:11:18.020 --> 00:11:21.730
So if you're going
down the diagonal,

00:11:21.730 --> 00:11:24.820
you're reading the
coefficient of variation,

00:11:24.820 --> 00:11:27.040
and then above and
below the diagonal,

00:11:27.040 --> 00:11:33.190
you're reading the
correlation of, say,

00:11:33.190 --> 00:11:37.975
in this case, livestock
income with profit income.

00:11:37.975 --> 00:11:40.600
It just throws you off, because
it should be written down here.

00:11:40.600 --> 00:11:42.763
And then to avoid
double counting,

00:11:42.763 --> 00:11:44.555
you don't fill in the
bottom of the matrix.

00:11:50.470 --> 00:11:53.470
So I've shown you
this picture before,

00:11:53.470 --> 00:12:01.458
the Rocky Mountain picture,
arguably the most famous graph

00:12:01.458 --> 00:12:02.250
I've ever produced.

00:12:04.980 --> 00:12:07.920
This is 10 years of data.

00:12:07.920 --> 00:12:10.260
And then the households
are lined up--

00:12:10.260 --> 00:12:13.500
which is why I keep showing it--

00:12:13.500 --> 00:12:15.270
the households are
lined up roughly

00:12:15.270 --> 00:12:17.800
by the size of landholdings.

00:12:17.800 --> 00:12:22.800
And you can see the levels
kind of going up as they

00:12:22.800 --> 00:12:26.250
have more and more land.

00:12:26.250 --> 00:12:30.270
And there's a 0 here.

00:12:30.270 --> 00:12:32.220
And so everything
on this diagram

00:12:32.220 --> 00:12:37.170
is deviation from the village
average at a point in time.

00:12:37.170 --> 00:12:39.900
Some people are below and
some people are above.

00:12:42.750 --> 00:12:45.240
You're seeing that
in the cross section,

00:12:45.240 --> 00:12:48.270
and you're seeing
that over time.

00:12:48.270 --> 00:12:50.100
The point of the diagram,
I've said before,

00:12:50.100 --> 00:12:52.800
is that some of the valleys
lie behind the peaks.

00:12:52.800 --> 00:12:56.130
And that means not everyone
is experiencing good years

00:12:56.130 --> 00:12:59.970
and bad years at the same time.

00:12:59.970 --> 00:13:06.420
It's not like undulating
waves of grain, as in Kansas.

00:13:06.420 --> 00:13:08.760
This is the consumption
picture that

00:13:08.760 --> 00:13:11.940
is on the same scale
as the income picture.

00:13:11.940 --> 00:13:14.130
If I wanted to get
bigger differences,

00:13:14.130 --> 00:13:17.690
I could rescale this graph.

00:13:17.690 --> 00:13:19.710
You know, it's all just
suppressed down there.

00:13:22.740 --> 00:13:26.160
But the statistical
work is really

00:13:26.160 --> 00:13:29.760
testing to see if there
are common fixed effects,

00:13:29.760 --> 00:13:34.090
and also whether this diagram
somehow, through the lens

00:13:34.090 --> 00:13:37.480
of the model, is related to
the income diagram previously.

00:13:38.835 --> 00:13:40.543
AUDIENCE: Have you
observed this in terms

00:13:40.543 --> 00:13:42.983
of like greater
weights on people?

00:13:42.983 --> 00:13:45.150
Because it looks like there's
not only risk-sharing,

00:13:45.150 --> 00:13:48.000
but also the rich guys are--

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:49.350
if it's the same [INAUDIBLE].

00:13:49.350 --> 00:13:50.175
ROBERT TOWNSEND: Yeah, exactly.

00:13:50.175 --> 00:13:51.830
AUDIENCE: They're not
just getting the average.

00:13:51.830 --> 00:13:53.080
ROBERT TOWNSEND: That's right.

00:13:53.080 --> 00:13:55.530
So risk-sharing is
sometimes misinterpreted

00:13:55.530 --> 00:13:59.170
to mean complete pooling, and
everyone has an equal share.

00:13:59.170 --> 00:14:00.660
And that's not necessary.

00:14:00.660 --> 00:14:03.360
And when we look at the
benchmark regression,

00:14:03.360 --> 00:14:05.050
essentially it
has fixed effects.

00:14:05.050 --> 00:14:07.860
And those fixed effects
are almost exactly

00:14:07.860 --> 00:14:11.070
the Pareto weights.

00:14:11.070 --> 00:14:12.810
And then we can
test and see what

00:14:12.810 --> 00:14:14.340
those weights are related to.

00:14:20.230 --> 00:14:25.510
So here's the
optimization problem.

00:14:25.510 --> 00:14:30.010
You just basically-- there
is a one-to-one relationship

00:14:30.010 --> 00:14:35.230
between all the Pareto-optimal
allocations in this economy

00:14:35.230 --> 00:14:38.350
and solutions to this
programming problem.

00:14:42.236 --> 00:14:44.570
And that's asking about
the Pareto weights.

00:14:44.570 --> 00:14:47.720
Here they are-- lambda
sub-k, different

00:14:47.720 --> 00:14:50.000
for different households, k.

00:14:50.000 --> 00:14:53.120
The household is the
basic unit, although we

00:14:53.120 --> 00:14:54.860
will control for
the demographics

00:14:54.860 --> 00:14:56.700
within the household.

00:14:56.700 --> 00:15:00.720
So just to read
across this, it's

00:15:00.720 --> 00:15:04.470
a weighted average, lambda,
Pareto-weighted average

00:15:04.470 --> 00:15:09.060
of the discounted
expected utility of, say,

00:15:09.060 --> 00:15:11.610
in this case, household k.

00:15:11.610 --> 00:15:15.410
OK, so it's over time, which
could be finite or infinite.

00:15:15.410 --> 00:15:17.850
It's discounted
at a common rate.

00:15:17.850 --> 00:15:19.510
I'll come back to that.

00:15:19.510 --> 00:15:21.720
It's presumed everyone
has equal probability

00:15:21.720 --> 00:15:23.310
over these states of the world.

00:15:26.520 --> 00:15:32.070
And these states of
the world are not just

00:15:32.070 --> 00:15:36.200
the contemporaneous
realization of all the shocks.

00:15:36.200 --> 00:15:40.580
It's the entire history, from
the initial date out to that,

00:15:40.580 --> 00:15:42.350
like the branches of a tree.

00:15:45.420 --> 00:15:47.610
And then utility
contemporaneously

00:15:47.610 --> 00:15:54.550
depends on consumption and
these gender/age weights.

00:15:54.550 --> 00:16:00.480
So and you just want to--
whatever sums of consumption

00:16:00.480 --> 00:16:03.090
is, it's this average
and the aggregate.

00:16:03.090 --> 00:16:05.460
And then the idea is how to
distribute that aggregate

00:16:05.460 --> 00:16:07.365
to maximize this
subjective function.

00:16:09.970 --> 00:16:12.520
You can put labor in here.

00:16:12.520 --> 00:16:14.020
We'll have a whole
lecture on that.

00:16:16.470 --> 00:16:17.470
So what is the solution?

00:16:20.140 --> 00:16:24.280
Let's just pick consumption
of household k at date t

00:16:24.280 --> 00:16:26.800
is entering in here,
and it's entering

00:16:26.800 --> 00:16:28.030
in this resource constraint.

00:16:28.030 --> 00:16:30.850
This supplies, you know, for
the whole history of states

00:16:30.850 --> 00:16:34.300
up to date, t,
for every date, t.

00:16:34.300 --> 00:16:37.030
So we're going to
get derivative here,

00:16:37.030 --> 00:16:38.650
and a Lagrange multiplier here.

00:16:38.650 --> 00:16:40.700
This is common
resource constraints.

00:16:40.700 --> 00:16:43.660
So you pick up a common
Lagrange multiplier.

00:16:43.660 --> 00:16:44.946
Yes.

00:16:44.946 --> 00:16:48.390
AUDIENCE: Does the [? ht ?]
include the use of [INAUDIBLE]

00:16:48.390 --> 00:16:49.520
ROBERT TOWNSEND: Yes.

00:16:49.520 --> 00:16:50.020
Yep.

00:16:52.790 --> 00:16:57.040
A complete enumeration of
everything, and not just crops,

00:16:57.040 --> 00:17:00.700
but babies, and deaths, and the
whole demographic structure.

00:17:08.230 --> 00:17:10.869
So again, taking
that derivative,

00:17:10.869 --> 00:17:12.400
putting this thing
over here, you'd

00:17:12.400 --> 00:17:17.260
get a beta-discounted
probability, lambda k weighted

00:17:17.260 --> 00:17:18.280
marginal utility.

00:17:18.280 --> 00:17:20.410
And everyone's margin
utility is being

00:17:20.410 --> 00:17:23.680
equated to this common
Lagrange multiplier.

00:17:29.480 --> 00:17:36.020
You know, so if you assumed a
particular exponential utility

00:17:36.020 --> 00:17:40.190
function, for example,
then you can actually

00:17:40.190 --> 00:17:42.680
get sort of closed-form
analytic solutions

00:17:42.680 --> 00:17:44.820
for these first-order
conditions.

00:17:44.820 --> 00:17:47.240
So this just says, in
levels, that the consumption

00:17:47.240 --> 00:17:50.180
of household k depends
on the Pareto--

00:17:50.180 --> 00:17:53.510
the log Pareto weight
of household k.

00:17:53.510 --> 00:17:57.080
It has something to do with
the demographics and something

00:17:57.080 --> 00:18:00.260
to do with this common
shadow price of consumption,

00:18:00.260 --> 00:18:01.610
if I dare call it that.

00:18:06.350 --> 00:18:08.980
So here are the levels that
we were just talking about.

00:18:14.290 --> 00:18:17.260
This is too small to
read, but basically--

00:18:25.090 --> 00:18:27.850
another nice thing about
that exponential utility,

00:18:27.850 --> 00:18:29.740
if you're willing to
make strong assumptions

00:18:29.740 --> 00:18:33.190
about the composition
of the household,

00:18:33.190 --> 00:18:37.520
is it basically would
dictate how to weight people.

00:18:37.520 --> 00:18:43.890
And little babies don't eat
as much as 18-year-old males.

00:18:43.890 --> 00:18:50.110
And in turn, consumption is
dropping for the elderly.

00:18:50.110 --> 00:18:52.260
So we actually had
a dietary survey.

00:18:52.260 --> 00:18:55.240
And we assumed that
strong functional form,

00:18:55.240 --> 00:18:56.900
and we made all
those corrections.

00:18:56.900 --> 00:19:01.560
So you don't actually
see people eating.

00:19:01.560 --> 00:19:04.320
So you don't see their
individual consumptions.

00:19:04.320 --> 00:19:09.900
You see the consumption
for the whole household, k,

00:19:09.900 --> 00:19:12.840
but you put it in per
capita terms by dividing

00:19:12.840 --> 00:19:17.460
by the age/gender-weighted
number of people.

00:19:17.460 --> 00:19:20.520
Likewise, this
thing over here is

00:19:20.520 --> 00:19:26.000
the sum in the whole population
of per-capita consumption.

00:19:26.000 --> 00:19:30.570
And sort of reading
out loud, this term

00:19:30.570 --> 00:19:35.850
is actually the risk tolerance,
the inverse risk aversion,

00:19:35.850 --> 00:19:36.825
of household k.

00:19:41.580 --> 00:19:42.890
It's actually a j here.

00:19:42.890 --> 00:19:44.300
Sorry.

00:19:44.300 --> 00:19:46.730
Household j relative
to the sum of the risk

00:19:46.730 --> 00:19:51.200
tolerances of all
the other households.

00:19:51.200 --> 00:19:54.880
And I'll come back
to this often.

00:19:54.880 --> 00:19:59.140
If you assumed homogeneous risk
aversion, which is standard,

00:19:59.140 --> 00:20:02.660
then this ought to have
a coefficient of 1.

00:20:02.660 --> 00:20:05.740
So everybody's consumption
is co-moving, one to one,

00:20:05.740 --> 00:20:09.560
with the per capita average.

00:20:09.560 --> 00:20:11.600
If you have different
risk aversions,

00:20:11.600 --> 00:20:14.060
there is a very nice
interpretation here, which

00:20:14.060 --> 00:20:16.010
is this is aggregate risk.

00:20:16.010 --> 00:20:18.800
This is what's left over
after all the other smoothing

00:20:18.800 --> 00:20:20.900
that they're doing
intertemporally, blah, blah,

00:20:20.900 --> 00:20:24.470
blah, than what
they actually eat.

00:20:24.470 --> 00:20:27.320
So this is like the macro risk.

00:20:27.320 --> 00:20:32.000
And then the higher this
risk tolerance, the more they

00:20:32.000 --> 00:20:36.740
should be willing to bear
that, quote, "helping"

00:20:36.740 --> 00:20:39.610
out their village neighbors
who might be quite risk-averse.

00:20:42.920 --> 00:20:44.480
And we'll come back
to that in terms

00:20:44.480 --> 00:20:47.290
of measuring risk aversion.

00:20:47.290 --> 00:20:50.020
OK, so here's the standard
regression equation.

00:20:50.020 --> 00:20:54.500
If the level of consumption
depends on basically

00:20:54.500 --> 00:20:59.350
what is now a constant
household-specific term, which

00:20:59.350 --> 00:21:02.960
are those Pareto weights,
sum-- coefficients, time,

00:21:02.960 --> 00:21:06.380
village average
consumption-- at date t,

00:21:06.380 --> 00:21:08.840
adjustment for demographics,
and something else that

00:21:08.840 --> 00:21:12.420
ought to be zero, like income.

00:21:20.250 --> 00:21:23.490
You're going to have a devil
of a time running this.

00:21:23.490 --> 00:21:28.160
Even when you run one
household at a time ignoring

00:21:28.160 --> 00:21:32.360
all the others, even when
you use the leave out mean--

00:21:32.360 --> 00:21:35.060
so the household
is not included--

00:21:35.060 --> 00:21:36.950
it will turn out,
amazingly enough,

00:21:36.950 --> 00:21:42.260
that these coefficients,
one for each household, when

00:21:42.260 --> 00:21:47.860
you average them up, have
to take on the value of 1.

00:21:47.860 --> 00:21:53.230
So there are sort of
econometric issues

00:21:53.230 --> 00:21:57.160
here that you could
mistakenly think

00:21:57.160 --> 00:21:58.882
that you've got a
lot of co-movement,

00:21:58.882 --> 00:22:01.090
and it's just going to
happen-- you know, why is this

00:22:01.090 --> 00:22:02.620
happening, essentially?

00:22:02.620 --> 00:22:06.610
Well, it's more obvious if you
had the panel in front of us

00:22:06.610 --> 00:22:08.440
rather than one
household at a time.

00:22:08.440 --> 00:22:11.920
You're looking at household
consumption on the left,

00:22:11.920 --> 00:22:14.980
and the average of household
consumption on the right.

00:22:14.980 --> 00:22:18.020
Now take the average
of the whole thing,

00:22:18.020 --> 00:22:20.350
and the averages appearing
on the left and the right,

00:22:20.350 --> 00:22:22.210
and it ought to take
on a value of 1.

00:22:22.210 --> 00:22:25.630
So the average tendency
of the dependent variable

00:22:25.630 --> 00:22:28.570
is kind of like an intercept.

00:22:28.570 --> 00:22:30.430
So that's kind of the intuition.

00:22:30.430 --> 00:22:34.780
This also comes up in
many situations where you

00:22:34.780 --> 00:22:36.770
have this confounding problem.

00:22:36.770 --> 00:22:37.270
Yes.

00:22:37.270 --> 00:22:39.645
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] talked
about [? instead of their ?]

00:22:39.645 --> 00:22:40.690
[? compatibility? ?]

00:22:40.690 --> 00:22:42.357
ROBERT TOWNSEND: No,
because we're going

00:22:42.357 --> 00:22:44.110
to assume full commitment--

00:22:44.110 --> 00:22:45.408
instead of compatibility?

00:22:45.408 --> 00:22:46.450
Did I hear you correctly?

00:22:46.450 --> 00:22:47.033
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:22:47.033 --> 00:22:48.550
ROBERT TOWNSEND: Yeah.

00:22:48.550 --> 00:22:52.630
We can put in
incentive constraints.

00:22:52.630 --> 00:22:54.880
And we will later.

00:22:54.880 --> 00:22:58.660
So we're going to build
on this basic framework,

00:22:58.660 --> 00:23:00.700
and get to all the
obstacles to trade,

00:23:00.700 --> 00:23:03.240
and how to estimate them.

00:23:03.240 --> 00:23:07.250
But you may think this thing
would be rejected out of hand.

00:23:07.250 --> 00:23:10.100
And it is statistically
rejected most of the time.

00:23:10.100 --> 00:23:13.520
But it turns out to be a
very, very useful benchmark.

00:23:18.830 --> 00:23:23.300
So this is the time series,
one household at a time.

00:23:23.300 --> 00:23:25.030
I won't say much
about this other

00:23:25.030 --> 00:23:27.260
than, does the data
have any power.

00:23:27.260 --> 00:23:31.070
The problem is, you test one
null, like full risk-sharing.

00:23:31.070 --> 00:23:33.500
And you can't reject it because
the confidence intervals

00:23:33.500 --> 00:23:34.310
are so large.

00:23:34.310 --> 00:23:37.700
So you want to test other
things like its autarky.

00:23:37.700 --> 00:23:40.940
And the weight of the
evidence is it's not autarky.

00:23:40.940 --> 00:23:43.265
We can pretty much
soundly reject--

00:23:48.858 --> 00:23:50.400
And risk-sharing is
doing quite well.

00:23:50.400 --> 00:23:52.300
And this is with a panel.

00:23:52.300 --> 00:23:54.920
And again, I'm going to
spare you all the details.

00:23:54.920 --> 00:23:56.940
But we did it three
different ways--

00:23:56.940 --> 00:24:02.790
standard, first
difference, Jerry Hausman--

00:24:02.790 --> 00:24:04.050
and estimated.

00:24:04.050 --> 00:24:06.510
Now, here we're
picking up coefficients

00:24:06.510 --> 00:24:09.960
on various sources of
income, none of which

00:24:09.960 --> 00:24:11.940
should be positive
and significant.

00:24:11.940 --> 00:24:14.670
But some of them kind of are.

00:24:14.670 --> 00:24:17.430
For example, the
highest number here

00:24:17.430 --> 00:24:21.100
is profits from trade and
handicrafts in Aurepalle.

00:24:21.100 --> 00:24:24.810
They're climbing palm
trees and tapping--

00:24:24.810 --> 00:24:27.270
and then making liquor, toddy.

00:24:30.540 --> 00:24:32.280
And it's not insured, evidently.

00:24:34.980 --> 00:24:40.860
Labor in general has a
high number pretty much

00:24:40.860 --> 00:24:42.160
in all the villages.

00:24:42.160 --> 00:24:46.680
So now we're kind of easing
into the policy thing, which

00:24:46.680 --> 00:24:49.080
is, if you wanted a
target, wouldn't you

00:24:49.080 --> 00:24:51.150
want to run this thing
first and see who's

00:24:51.150 --> 00:24:54.720
the most vulnerable,
and then sort of guide

00:24:54.720 --> 00:24:56.460
your interventions.

00:24:56.460 --> 00:24:58.990
Based on that, I wasn't
thinking along that line,

00:24:58.990 --> 00:25:01.530
I was just being
honest about where

00:25:01.530 --> 00:25:03.300
we're rejecting and so on.

00:25:07.790 --> 00:25:13.790
And here, finally, Matt, is
where we took this coefficient

00:25:13.790 --> 00:25:19.680
and regressed it
against other things

00:25:19.680 --> 00:25:24.840
like the area operated by
the household, the value

00:25:24.840 --> 00:25:27.990
of their plow animals,
their inheritance,

00:25:27.990 --> 00:25:29.250
and so on and so forth.

00:25:32.760 --> 00:25:34.530
And I'm not sure what
you would expect.

00:25:34.530 --> 00:25:38.220
It looks good at first
blush, in the sense

00:25:38.220 --> 00:25:41.910
that the amount of land and
the value of the animals

00:25:41.910 --> 00:25:44.172
is correlated with
those intercepts.

00:25:47.130 --> 00:25:51.240
The problem is things are
more turbulent than that

00:25:51.240 --> 00:25:52.290
at the village level.

00:25:52.290 --> 00:25:55.140
And people do sell, or
buy, or acquire land.

00:25:55.140 --> 00:25:57.990
And certainly those
plow animals aren't just

00:25:57.990 --> 00:26:01.650
locked in place year
after year after year.

00:26:01.650 --> 00:26:05.070
So that's kind of some
evidence of some kind

00:26:05.070 --> 00:26:10.740
of long-term impact that shows
up in terms of the assets

00:26:10.740 --> 00:26:12.570
they end up holding.

00:26:12.570 --> 00:26:14.460
And that's very much
along the lines of,

00:26:14.460 --> 00:26:17.820
is there a moral hazard
problem or some kind

00:26:17.820 --> 00:26:19.140
of incentive constraint?

00:26:19.140 --> 00:26:24.300
And how should wealth levels
behave if that were the case?

00:26:28.170 --> 00:26:31.970
The biggest puzzle in
these data, in some sense,

00:26:31.970 --> 00:26:38.670
is almost the opposite,
which is although we see them

00:26:38.670 --> 00:26:48.150
over 10 years, we see the
upper-caste, white-robed

00:26:48.150 --> 00:26:51.540
brahman-type guys in the
village just consistently eating

00:26:51.540 --> 00:26:55.270
far less than their
income, constantly.

00:26:55.270 --> 00:26:58.470
And so is this just a
social transfer mechanism,

00:26:58.470 --> 00:27:01.680
or are they actually
insuring themselves

00:27:01.680 --> 00:27:05.760
against future relabeling of--

00:27:05.760 --> 00:27:07.590
castes, by the way
do get relabeled,

00:27:07.590 --> 00:27:09.070
and histories get recreated.

00:27:09.070 --> 00:27:13.730
It it's a much more complicated
history than you might--

00:27:13.730 --> 00:27:17.130
at least that's what the
anthropologists tell me.

00:27:17.130 --> 00:27:25.970
OK, so that's risk and
insurance in village India.

00:27:30.020 --> 00:27:32.840
So let's take that framework
and start knocking off

00:27:32.840 --> 00:27:34.180
some policy questions.

00:27:34.180 --> 00:27:38.930
So first is about
the effectiveness

00:27:38.930 --> 00:27:40.310
of financial institutions.

00:27:40.310 --> 00:27:45.410
Now, let me just say, the
immediate policy implication

00:27:45.410 --> 00:27:50.870
coming out of village
India was basically,

00:27:50.870 --> 00:27:56.200
miraculously, somehow,
they're pooling all that risk.

00:27:56.200 --> 00:28:00.480
It's not a bunch of fragmented
households on their own,

00:28:00.480 --> 00:28:01.830
in autarky.

00:28:01.830 --> 00:28:04.380
It seems to be
more the opposite.

00:28:04.380 --> 00:28:08.010
So there was a huge
firestorm people

00:28:08.010 --> 00:28:11.790
had a hard time accepting
that something like that

00:28:11.790 --> 00:28:12.420
could happen.

00:28:15.450 --> 00:28:18.900
But villages, even if they
were amazingly good not,

00:28:18.900 --> 00:28:22.440
are not necessarily
interacting with each other.

00:28:22.440 --> 00:28:24.150
I'll come back to that.

00:28:24.150 --> 00:28:27.420
And there may be, as there
is in Thailand, transactions

00:28:27.420 --> 00:28:29.230
with outside financial
institutions.

00:28:29.230 --> 00:28:33.990
So the question is, do outside
formal financial institutions

00:28:33.990 --> 00:28:39.070
help, if not within the
village, then across village,

00:28:39.070 --> 00:28:41.350
in the mitigation of risk?

00:28:48.380 --> 00:28:51.610
So roughly speaking,
the treatment group

00:28:51.610 --> 00:28:54.640
is a set of households
who are customers

00:28:54.640 --> 00:28:56.710
of financial institutions.

00:28:56.710 --> 00:28:57.760
A little typo there.

00:29:00.790 --> 00:29:03.940
And that's measured-- their
use of the institution

00:29:03.940 --> 00:29:07.450
is actually measured in the
data, which is reassuring.

00:29:07.450 --> 00:29:13.060
And I'll tell you about the
instruments we use momentarily.

00:29:13.060 --> 00:29:15.580
So we're going to go back to
that consumption equation,

00:29:15.580 --> 00:29:21.100
and also derive a corresponding
investment equation,

00:29:21.100 --> 00:29:27.250
and then see whether being
a customer or a member

00:29:27.250 --> 00:29:29.260
lowers the vulnerability
in the sense

00:29:29.260 --> 00:29:31.940
of that coefficient
on idiosyncratic risk.

00:29:31.940 --> 00:29:32.440
Yes.

00:29:32.440 --> 00:29:36.050
AUDIENCE: So when we say
those with financial access

00:29:36.050 --> 00:29:38.290
are compared to those
without, so does

00:29:38.290 --> 00:29:40.420
that really mean
those with access

00:29:40.420 --> 00:29:43.187
to the formal financial
sector are compared without--

00:29:43.187 --> 00:29:44.770
ROBERT TOWNSEND:
That's what it means.

00:29:44.770 --> 00:29:46.600
AUDIENCE: Yeah, because
there's money-lending sectors

00:29:46.600 --> 00:29:46.820
et cetera.

00:29:46.820 --> 00:29:47.500
ROBERT TOWNSEND: Exactly.

00:29:47.500 --> 00:29:48.430
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:29:48.430 --> 00:29:52.350
ROBERT TOWNSEND: So yeah,
that's like one topic away.

00:29:52.350 --> 00:29:55.270
I'll come right back to that.

00:29:55.270 --> 00:29:58.240
But to answer your
question, it's

00:29:58.240 --> 00:30:01.270
going to turn out that
directly connected,

00:30:01.270 --> 00:30:05.020
at least in consumption,
is helpful, but indirectly

00:30:05.020 --> 00:30:07.810
connected, through
gifts and loans

00:30:07.810 --> 00:30:10.660
to someone in the village,
even though you're not,

00:30:10.660 --> 00:30:14.230
is as effective in
consumption-smoothing.

00:30:14.230 --> 00:30:20.350
So that's then consistent
with the previous paper,

00:30:20.350 --> 00:30:22.875
although it's not quite
so clean with investment.

00:30:30.620 --> 00:30:32.080
So what are these institutions?

00:30:32.080 --> 00:30:35.470
Well, by now you probably
know the names of them.

00:30:35.470 --> 00:30:39.640
They've been coming up
in previous lectures.

00:30:39.640 --> 00:30:42.660
We find that this
bank for agriculture

00:30:42.660 --> 00:30:45.460
and agricultural cooperatives
is helpful in smoothing

00:30:45.460 --> 00:30:46.840
consumption and investment.

00:30:46.840 --> 00:30:49.300
It looks, from the
transactions data,

00:30:49.300 --> 00:30:52.390
is if that has to do with
its credit operation.

00:30:52.390 --> 00:30:55.180
They're basically embedding
credit and insurance

00:30:55.180 --> 00:30:57.640
in their loan contracts.

00:30:57.640 --> 00:31:01.000
It's not, "you pay back
the loan or default."

00:31:01.000 --> 00:31:04.900
There's a whole
schedule for repayment.

00:31:04.900 --> 00:31:09.470
And it's adjusted by aggregate
local/regional shocks,

00:31:09.470 --> 00:31:10.990
and so on.

00:31:10.990 --> 00:31:15.260
It's quite sophisticated.

00:31:15.260 --> 00:31:18.260
In the financial
crisis, the World Bank

00:31:18.260 --> 00:31:22.190
went in there determined to
see this stereotype everywhere,

00:31:22.190 --> 00:31:26.330
since remember, finance
companies and commercial bank

00:31:26.330 --> 00:31:29.270
failures triggered the
Asia financial crisis.

00:31:32.070 --> 00:31:35.870
So they looked at the BAAC
history of over arrears,

00:31:35.870 --> 00:31:38.300
and concluded that it
was another disaster.

00:31:38.300 --> 00:31:41.870
But actually they were running
an insurance operation.

00:31:41.870 --> 00:31:44.140
And that's what shows up
in the consumption data.

00:31:46.780 --> 00:31:49.240
Commercial banks are
helping to smooth somewhat.

00:31:49.240 --> 00:31:53.770
It's largely, though, through
formal savings accounts.

00:31:53.770 --> 00:31:55.720
Loans are pretty
thin in the data.

00:32:00.380 --> 00:32:02.920
So what are we going to do?

00:32:02.920 --> 00:32:05.680
You've seen this model before.

00:32:05.680 --> 00:32:08.720
This is Greenwood and Javanovic.

00:32:08.720 --> 00:32:14.570
By the way, we're sort of in the
data micro part of the class.

00:32:14.570 --> 00:32:17.470
Don't forget about
all that macro.

00:32:17.470 --> 00:32:20.770
So the Greenwood-Jovanovic
model assumes

00:32:20.770 --> 00:32:23.620
that the benefit of being
in a financial institution

00:32:23.620 --> 00:32:28.390
is better information
and risk-sharing.

00:32:28.390 --> 00:32:31.120
So here we are
looking at the data

00:32:31.120 --> 00:32:33.730
to see if that's a
