00:55:11.010 --> 00:55:12.960
and so on.

00:55:21.840 --> 00:55:26.040
So to see how
we're estimating it

00:55:26.040 --> 00:55:32.760
and get some intuition for how
we estimate the risk aversion,

00:55:32.760 --> 00:55:36.600
if two households had more
or less the same coefficient

00:55:36.600 --> 00:55:38.610
of risk tolerance,
then their consumption

00:55:38.610 --> 00:55:41.760
should more or
less move together.

00:55:41.760 --> 00:55:45.300
But the opposite, if one were
very almost risk-neutral,

00:55:45.300 --> 00:55:50.580
and the other very risk-averse,
then, practically, consumption

00:55:50.580 --> 00:55:54.600
is almost smooth
for the risk-averse

00:55:54.600 --> 00:55:58.290
guy by virtue of
the risk-neutral guy

00:55:58.290 --> 00:56:00.480
underwriting that risk.

00:56:00.480 --> 00:56:05.250
So you can imagine-- and
people have done this--

00:56:05.250 --> 00:56:07.860
looking at households
pairwise, and just

00:56:07.860 --> 00:56:10.470
trying to see how many
consumption reversals there

00:56:10.470 --> 00:56:11.730
are, and things.

00:56:11.730 --> 00:56:12.990
We don't quite do that.

00:56:12.990 --> 00:56:15.930
We don't have enough data.

00:56:15.930 --> 00:56:18.750
And I'm not sure it's very
effective econometrically.

00:56:18.750 --> 00:56:24.510
We do take a household, j, take
their measure of co-movement,

00:56:24.510 --> 00:56:27.480
essentially, compared to
the co-movements of all

00:56:27.480 --> 00:56:29.200
the other households.

00:56:29.200 --> 00:56:32.600
So it's always j,
less time, compared

00:56:32.600 --> 00:56:33.600
with all the other ones.

00:56:33.600 --> 00:56:36.670
Well, it's probably easier
to do it with the notation.

00:56:36.670 --> 00:56:41.190
So here is that basic
first-order condition.

00:56:41.190 --> 00:56:44.010
With constant relative
risk-aversion, by the way,

00:56:44.010 --> 00:56:47.610
it's in logs, not levels.

00:56:47.610 --> 00:56:48.930
But it's the same idea.

00:56:48.930 --> 00:56:51.240
You've got the Pareto weight.

00:56:51.240 --> 00:56:56.340
We're actually going to allow
differences in discount rates

00:56:56.340 --> 00:56:58.480
across households.

00:56:58.480 --> 00:57:01.830
And so that sends
sets up a trend,

00:57:01.830 --> 00:57:06.740
where some people are going up
and some people are going down

00:57:06.740 --> 00:57:07.800
long term.

00:57:07.800 --> 00:57:09.720
We allow preference shocks--

00:57:09.720 --> 00:57:14.550
actually monthly shocks, because
there are holidays and things.

00:57:14.550 --> 00:57:17.790
So the idea is to put as many
controls in, in some sense,

00:57:17.790 --> 00:57:19.680
that the theory would allow.

00:57:19.680 --> 00:57:24.660
And then we have this sort
of common fixed effect.

00:57:24.660 --> 00:57:30.300
And note in particular
that actually everything,

00:57:30.300 --> 00:57:33.210
but in particular this
thing, is normalized

00:57:33.210 --> 00:57:41.110
by basically the risk aversion.

00:57:41.110 --> 00:57:45.760
If risk aversion is really high,
this coefficient is really low,

00:57:45.760 --> 00:57:48.850
and so that household's
not moving around

00:57:48.850 --> 00:57:50.117
with the aggregate.

00:57:54.990 --> 00:57:59.730
So basically-- sorry--
almost what we're doing

00:57:59.730 --> 00:58:02.430
is taking consumption,
regressing it

00:58:02.430 --> 00:58:05.850
against trends, and
monthly effects,

00:58:05.850 --> 00:58:10.800
and household fixed effects,
and getting a residual.

00:58:10.800 --> 00:58:13.260
The residual is
capturing all of this--

00:58:13.260 --> 00:58:17.660
call it v or eta, and
then just sort of see.

00:58:17.660 --> 00:58:21.900
What the correlation
is between a household

00:58:21.900 --> 00:58:27.510
i's residual, which is a
stand-in for that aggregate

00:58:27.510 --> 00:58:31.560
that's moving consumption, and
any other household's i-prime.

00:58:34.130 --> 00:58:36.990
So this is like a
moment, basically.

00:58:36.990 --> 00:58:41.150
And we can use
method of moments,

00:58:41.150 --> 00:58:44.670
in principle, for all
the households, pairwise.

00:58:44.670 --> 00:58:47.850
But we didn't have
enough data for that,

00:58:47.850 --> 00:58:50.870
even though we have a lot of
households and a lot of months.

00:58:50.870 --> 00:58:53.960
So we just summed that we have
