01:03:45.140 --> 01:03:46.640
To try to say it
in words, we're not

01:03:46.640 --> 01:03:48.680
looking at some indirect
utility function.

01:03:48.680 --> 01:03:51.490
We're looking at the
direct utility function.

01:03:51.490 --> 01:03:54.815
And indirect might be there if
they have other ways of coping.

01:03:57.710 --> 01:04:00.410
When we get to labor
supply, we will

01:04:00.410 --> 01:04:03.650
be quite explicit
about supplying labor

01:04:03.650 --> 01:04:06.880
as a way to cope with risk, and
then revisit these equations.

01:04:15.990 --> 01:04:21.310
So people have--

01:04:21.310 --> 01:04:26.200
I have, too-- offered insurance
products like rainfall

01:04:26.200 --> 01:04:28.840
insurance in India.

01:04:28.840 --> 01:04:32.220
We haven't quite done
it yet in Thailand.

01:04:32.220 --> 01:04:36.550
And I'll tell you why we
have misgivings about it,

01:04:36.550 --> 01:04:37.690
and some of the puzzles.

01:04:37.690 --> 01:04:42.480
But basically with less of an
exception in Ghana and Chris

01:04:42.480 --> 01:04:45.940
Udry, with Dean,
most experiments

01:04:45.940 --> 01:04:48.370
in the world, the take-up
of these insurance products

01:04:48.370 --> 01:04:49.450
is pretty low.

01:04:49.450 --> 01:04:53.800
Or in our case, in India,
people will insure one plot,

01:04:53.800 --> 01:04:56.890
and not insure the other
plots that they own.

01:04:56.890 --> 01:05:01.270
So you know, it's
not totally terrible.

01:05:01.270 --> 01:05:03.160
There is some price elasticity.

01:05:03.160 --> 01:05:05.680
But there are puzzles.

01:05:05.680 --> 01:05:08.710
I mean, if people are so
poor and so vulnerable,

01:05:08.710 --> 01:05:10.330
then why aren't
taking it up more?

01:05:10.330 --> 01:05:15.150
Now, one answer you
may have already seen.

01:05:15.150 --> 01:05:18.850
They don't really need it.

01:05:18.850 --> 01:05:20.858
Because even if they're
somewhat vulnerable,

01:05:20.858 --> 01:05:22.900
there are people in the
village willing to assume

01:05:22.900 --> 01:05:23.930
some of that risk.

01:05:23.930 --> 01:05:27.250
And even if it isn't perfect,
at the end of the day, given

01:05:27.250 --> 01:05:30.220
the way the policies
are priced, maybe you're

01:05:30.220 --> 01:05:32.470
just not going to
see that take-up.

01:05:32.470 --> 01:05:35.320
Unfortunately-- and people
aren't either taking

01:05:35.320 --> 01:05:40.480
the time to get baseline data
or don't bother with it at all.

01:05:40.480 --> 01:05:44.470
They just go in
there with an RCT.

01:05:44.470 --> 01:05:46.490
Well, we did.

01:05:46.490 --> 01:05:47.060
Yeah.

01:05:47.060 --> 01:05:50.246
AUDIENCE: So is that
just rainfall insurance?

01:05:50.246 --> 01:05:51.670
Or any kinds of insurance?

01:05:51.670 --> 01:05:53.860
ROBERT TOWNSEND:
Could be anything.

01:05:53.860 --> 01:05:55.930
I'm going to focus on
rainfall as just a way

01:05:55.930 --> 01:05:57.280
to give it a label.

01:05:57.280 --> 01:06:00.380
Could be any kind
of weather risk.

01:06:00.380 --> 01:06:03.880
It could actually be price risk.

01:06:03.880 --> 01:06:07.510
Case-Shiller index in the
US is about price risk.

01:06:07.510 --> 01:06:09.640
It wasn't just to
measure housing prices

01:06:09.640 --> 01:06:12.460
to get his name in The Wall
Street Journal every month.

01:06:12.460 --> 01:06:17.230
It was originally designed
because Bob Shiller had spent

01:06:17.230 --> 01:06:21.880
years creating a risk
instrument which he was trying

01:06:21.880 --> 01:06:24.790
to promote on Wall Street.

01:06:24.790 --> 01:06:26.510
So yeah, so it could be--

01:06:26.510 --> 01:06:28.450
and in urban areas,
maybe it is more

01:06:28.450 --> 01:06:34.090
likely to be vulnerability to
price rather than rainfall.

01:06:34.090 --> 01:06:37.420
So rainfall here is kind
of like, partly, a metaphor

01:06:37.420 --> 01:06:38.770
for the problem in general.

01:06:38.770 --> 01:06:41.680
But I'll come back
with a vengeance

01:06:41.680 --> 01:06:45.196
to look at rainfall in
these Thai villages.

01:06:45.196 --> 01:06:48.650
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
even summer and winter,

01:06:48.650 --> 01:06:52.783
they say that rain
affects [INAUDIBLE]..

01:06:52.783 --> 01:06:53.700
ROBERT TOWNSEND: Yeah.

01:06:53.700 --> 01:06:57.660
People don't come and buy
when it's raining, and so on.

01:06:57.660 --> 01:07:01.650
But you came up with a situation
where it was actually good.

01:07:01.650 --> 01:07:03.150
Just trying to
remember what it was.

01:07:03.150 --> 01:07:04.530
AUDIENCE: I think
we said, umbrellas.

01:07:04.530 --> 01:07:06.322
ROBERT TOWNSEND: Yeah,
something like that.

01:07:10.580 --> 01:07:17.690
OK, so here's the vengeance
paper with Kamilya.

01:07:17.690 --> 01:07:19.850
So this is all about rain.

01:07:19.850 --> 01:07:29.270
So we want to see the effect
of rain on rice production.

01:07:29.270 --> 01:07:31.940
Now again, the typical
thing that you'll

01:07:31.940 --> 01:07:33.440
see in the
development literature

01:07:33.440 --> 01:07:36.470
is rainfall is the risk.

01:07:36.470 --> 01:07:39.560
Let's just sort of instrument
the relevant variable

01:07:39.560 --> 01:07:43.340
by rainfall, and then
start looking at migration

01:07:43.340 --> 01:07:44.918
and all kinds of stuff.

01:07:44.918 --> 01:07:46.460
So here, the idea
is, let's just look

01:07:46.460 --> 01:07:50.110
at rainfall in the village,
start instrumenting income

01:07:50.110 --> 01:07:53.900
or rice production by
rainfall, and then look

01:07:53.900 --> 01:07:58.790
at the vulnerability
of consumption

01:07:58.790 --> 01:08:04.470
to instrumented income,
which people do, a lot.

01:08:04.470 --> 01:08:08.800
Now, it's going to
turn out that things

01:08:08.800 --> 01:08:11.500
are more complicated than
that within the village.

01:08:11.500 --> 01:08:12.670
The soil is different.

01:08:12.670 --> 01:08:15.220
The hydrology and water
flow are different.

01:08:15.220 --> 01:08:20.069
They actually plant
at different times.

01:08:20.069 --> 01:08:25.050
So a common rainfall shock,
even if it is actually common,

01:08:25.050 --> 01:08:28.770
and shows up and all the
rain gauges which we have,

01:08:28.770 --> 01:08:31.740
it's still the case that
it has differential impact

01:08:31.740 --> 01:08:36.990
on the households, especially
depending on when they plant,

01:08:36.990 --> 01:08:42.350
which is in turn a
function of soil and so on.

01:08:42.350 --> 01:08:44.859
So what are Kamilya and I doing?

01:08:44.859 --> 01:08:48.069
We're going to estimate
a three-stage production

01:08:48.069 --> 01:08:54.550
function which takes into
account the sequential nature.

01:08:54.550 --> 01:08:55.990
There's planting, for sure.

01:08:55.990 --> 01:08:59.680
And then you have sort of
the germination period,

01:08:59.680 --> 01:09:01.810
and the planting of
the rice, and so on,

01:09:01.810 --> 01:09:03.729
with maybe some
fertilizing and so on.

01:09:03.729 --> 01:09:05.925
Then you've got
sort of midseason,

01:09:05.925 --> 01:09:07.300
and all the stuff
you need to do.

01:09:07.300 --> 01:09:10.615
And then you finally
approach and include harvest.

01:09:14.040 --> 01:09:20.960
You know, I'm going to jump,
and just show you the notation.

01:09:20.960 --> 01:09:29.920
So here basically is stage
I, with predecessor stages I

01:09:29.920 --> 01:09:30.609
minus 1.

01:09:33.550 --> 01:09:36.250
It's going to be looking
forward to future stages

01:09:36.250 --> 01:09:38.870
if you're not at the last one.

01:09:38.870 --> 01:09:43.160
So if you're at the last one,
this would be the harvest.

01:09:43.160 --> 01:09:45.560
That's the easiest
thing to think about.

01:09:45.560 --> 01:09:47.569
If you're in the
next-to-last one,

01:09:47.569 --> 01:09:51.020
the output is
basically the condition

01:09:51.020 --> 01:09:54.410
of the crop prior to harvest.

01:09:54.410 --> 01:09:58.040
And what influences that?

01:09:58.040 --> 01:10:00.120
Well, if you've got
land, labor, capital,

01:10:00.120 --> 01:10:04.850
and so on, as Cobb-Douglas
type inputs in the production

01:10:04.850 --> 01:10:08.300
function--

01:10:08.300 --> 01:10:14.370
but you've also got the
state of the crop plot

01:10:14.370 --> 01:10:18.790
that you inherited from
the previous stage.

01:10:18.790 --> 01:10:21.130
And then all of this gets
hit, at the end of the period,

01:10:21.130 --> 01:10:24.565
with more shocks,
including rain, and so on,

01:10:24.565 --> 01:10:27.210
and temperature.

01:10:27.210 --> 01:10:30.870
So this is not a Cobb-Douglas.

01:10:30.870 --> 01:10:36.510
It's a CES that allows
some substitutability

01:10:36.510 --> 01:10:40.080
to be estimated between
the current state

01:10:40.080 --> 01:10:43.930
and contemporaneous inputs.

01:10:47.800 --> 01:10:50.890
It may not be as
extreme as Leontief.

01:10:50.890 --> 01:10:54.070
So you're kind of doomed by
the state of the crop plot

01:10:54.070 --> 01:10:56.620
at this time,
based on everything

01:10:56.620 --> 01:10:58.990
that happened in the past.

01:10:58.990 --> 01:11:01.660
And then you just have to
adjust inputs in proportion.

01:11:01.660 --> 01:11:04.240
Doesn't have to be that
bad, but it turns out

01:11:04.240 --> 01:11:06.263
not to be like Cobb-Douglas.

01:11:06.263 --> 01:11:07.930
If you want to think
about Cobb-Douglas,

01:11:07.930 --> 01:11:10.410
there's a whole lot
of substitutability--

01:11:10.410 --> 01:11:12.055
labor today, labor tomorrow.

01:11:12.055 --> 01:11:13.750
Oh, it's not that
much of a difference.

01:11:13.750 --> 01:11:17.230
Why don't we wait and figure
out what the rainfall is first,

01:11:17.230 --> 01:11:20.820
and then adjust
the inputs later?

01:11:20.820 --> 01:11:24.465
So this allows us to estimate
the ability to adjust.

01:11:27.350 --> 01:11:29.660
And essentially the
reason you can't

01:11:29.660 --> 01:11:33.200
use rain, aggregated up
over the whole season,

01:11:33.200 --> 01:11:35.840
is because of this
imperfect substitutability

01:11:35.840 --> 01:11:36.710
across the stages.

01:11:39.410 --> 01:11:40.078
Yep.

01:11:40.078 --> 01:11:43.420
AUDIENCE: It says
that it introduces--

01:11:43.420 --> 01:11:46.000
[INAUDIBLE] that
[INAUDIBLE] induces

01:11:46.000 --> 01:11:48.462
people to plant at different
times, for example.

01:11:48.462 --> 01:11:50.170
ROBERT TOWNSEND: No,
that's not in there.

01:11:50.170 --> 01:11:53.650
There's a separate equation
that has to do-- like a probit,

01:11:53.650 --> 01:11:57.310
basically, which determines
planting times as we see it

01:11:57.310 --> 01:11:58.000
in the data.

01:12:05.970 --> 01:12:16.870
So we can look at the effect
of rainfall on rice production.

01:12:16.870 --> 01:12:20.520
And we can actually do
something with climate change.

01:12:20.520 --> 01:12:23.430
Let me show you this thing.

01:12:23.430 --> 01:12:32.020
So this black thing
here is the distribution

01:12:32.020 --> 01:12:35.290
of actual yields
across households--

01:12:40.680 --> 01:12:42.710
and actually it's
households and time.

01:12:45.540 --> 01:12:55.340
This peak thing is just
using a weather index.

01:12:55.340 --> 01:12:57.860
So you regress yields--

01:12:57.860 --> 01:13:02.750
same data, our data, onto
temperature and rainfall,

01:13:02.750 --> 01:13:04.760
and a whole suite of
them, a big, long vector.

01:13:04.760 --> 01:13:07.420
It doesn't have to be,
narrowly, rainfall.

01:13:07.420 --> 01:13:10.510
Try to be as
realistic as possible.

01:13:10.510 --> 01:13:12.250
And then you run a regression.

01:13:12.250 --> 01:13:15.370
And then you get basically
the predicted through the lens

01:13:15.370 --> 01:13:20.570
of that weather index model.

01:13:20.570 --> 01:13:22.040
And it's close.

01:13:22.040 --> 01:13:23.370
It's very, very peaked.

01:13:26.450 --> 01:13:28.250
Well, sorry, that's
the first thing.

01:13:28.250 --> 01:13:31.350
Then this thing is
using the full model--

01:13:31.350 --> 01:13:34.610
sorry, using the model, but only
the observed rainfall variable,

01:13:34.610 --> 01:13:37.760
and setting everything else at
their sample average-- common

01:13:37.760 --> 01:13:42.110
soil, common fertilizer.

01:13:42.110 --> 01:13:47.120
And then the big jump
down here toward the data

01:13:47.120 --> 01:13:50.600
is when you start to allow the
variation that the model has

01:13:50.600 --> 01:13:56.850
in it, certainly soil variation,
and eventually full variation.

01:13:56.850 --> 01:14:01.580
So we're not one to one with
the actual distribution,

01:14:01.580 --> 01:14:03.980
but we've made a
substantial improvement

01:14:03.980 --> 01:14:06.440
from simple weather indices.

01:14:12.310 --> 01:14:15.910
So people talk about basis risk.

01:14:15.910 --> 01:14:18.400
And what they mean
typically is the reason

01:14:18.400 --> 01:14:20.500
there's not take-up of
a rainfall insurance

01:14:20.500 --> 01:14:24.340
product is because the rain
gauge is way out there,

01:14:24.340 --> 01:14:29.620
so distant that the correlation
of the rainfall at the gauge

01:14:29.620 --> 01:14:33.880
with the correlation of the
rainfall in the village is low.

01:14:33.880 --> 01:14:37.450
In fact, the Bank for
Agriculture introduced--

01:14:37.450 --> 01:14:40.150
I guess it's now
three years ago--

01:14:40.150 --> 01:14:43.460
an index product.

01:14:43.460 --> 01:14:46.270
And they already restricted
it to be something

01:14:46.270 --> 01:14:48.580
like 20, 25 kilometers.

01:14:48.580 --> 01:14:51.010
And the take-up was terrible.

01:14:51.010 --> 01:14:54.340
So then they said, oh,
we know, it's basis risk.

01:14:54.340 --> 01:14:57.460
So then they went down
to something like 15,

01:14:57.460 --> 01:14:59.860
lowered the radius.

01:14:59.860 --> 01:15:01.760
And take-up was
still pretty bad.

01:15:01.760 --> 01:15:04.177
And I think they're going to
have to withdraw the product.

01:15:06.580 --> 01:15:09.780
So this is a kind of basis risk.

01:15:09.780 --> 01:15:12.270
What we're saying
is, even though we're

01:15:12.270 --> 01:15:14.580
sitting on top of
the rainfall gauge,

01:15:14.580 --> 01:15:17.100
within the village, the
way that that rainfall

01:15:17.100 --> 01:15:22.710
is impacting these farmers is
different across the farmers.

01:15:22.710 --> 01:15:27.630
So we're busy sort of thinking
about designing, still,

01:15:27.630 --> 01:15:31.230
a rainfall product, but
trying to take into account

01:15:31.230 --> 01:15:32.320
this heterogeneity.

01:15:32.320 --> 01:15:32.820
Yes.

01:15:32.820 --> 01:15:35.112
AUDIENCE: Maybe this is kind
of what you're getting at,

01:15:35.112 --> 01:15:38.540
[INAUDIBLE] how flexible is the
sort of payout structure given?

01:15:38.540 --> 01:15:40.623
I'm just trying to-- because
it seems like there's

01:15:40.623 --> 01:15:42.340
kind of like, a [INAUDIBLE]

01:15:42.340 --> 01:15:46.210
ROBERT TOWNSEND: Yeah, so
let me show you Kapphan's--

01:15:48.850 --> 01:15:50.500
her dissertation.

01:15:58.710 --> 01:16:01.467
So here's her idea,
which is basically--

01:16:01.467 --> 01:16:03.050
and this is typical
of the literature.

01:16:03.050 --> 01:16:05.090
She did better than most.

01:16:05.090 --> 01:16:09.530
You have a utility
function over consumption.

01:16:09.530 --> 01:16:12.830
Consumption would
be autarky income.

01:16:12.830 --> 01:16:14.210
But you have a payout--

01:16:14.210 --> 01:16:16.640
could be positive or negative.

01:16:16.640 --> 01:16:20.720
And that's a function of
this weather index, z.

01:16:20.720 --> 01:16:23.210
So this is supposed
to be smoothing.

01:16:23.210 --> 01:16:26.600
And this is an optimal
design problem.

01:16:26.600 --> 01:16:29.472
It's output conditioned
on the weather index,

01:16:29.472 --> 01:16:31.430
and then the distribution
of the weather index.

01:16:31.430 --> 01:16:33.305
By the way, where is
she getting all of this?

01:16:33.305 --> 01:16:35.480
She's doing it in the lab.

01:16:35.480 --> 01:16:38.690
She's basically simulated
millet production

01:16:38.690 --> 01:16:40.460
in Switzerland or something.

01:16:40.460 --> 01:16:44.540
But she's not out looking
at the actual crops.

01:16:44.540 --> 01:16:46.605
AUDIENCE: Is that
[INAUDIBLE] soil?

01:16:46.605 --> 01:16:47.480
ROBERT TOWNSEND: Hmm?

01:16:47.480 --> 01:16:50.040
AUDIENCE: Is it
[INAUDIBLE] soil?

01:16:50.040 --> 01:16:51.800
ROBERT TOWNSEND: I
don't remember exactly.

01:16:51.800 --> 01:16:53.960
But that is a big
problem in practice

01:16:53.960 --> 01:16:57.140
when you take these sort
of lab-type experiments.

01:16:57.140 --> 01:17:00.670
I forgot to say, we actually
use a crop grow model as well.

01:17:00.670 --> 01:17:02.660
It's called DSSAT.

01:17:02.660 --> 01:17:08.060
And we carefully feed in soil
depth and soil into that model

01:17:08.060 --> 01:17:09.380
I just showed you.

01:17:09.380 --> 01:17:12.590
But to address
your question, sort

01:17:12.590 --> 01:17:15.960
of optimized over this thing,
this is the policy design.

01:17:15.960 --> 01:17:18.380
This is the optimal
contract design problem.

01:17:18.380 --> 01:17:19.660
How cool.

01:17:19.660 --> 01:17:21.970
I mean, it really is cool.

01:17:21.970 --> 01:17:28.110
And you know, you can see,
in her simulated data,

01:17:28.110 --> 01:17:30.360
the distribution of
yields for any index.

01:17:33.790 --> 01:17:36.960
And then here's the
optimized payout,

01:17:36.960 --> 01:17:42.270
which is basically positive,
definitely non-linear.

01:17:42.270 --> 01:17:45.220
And basically it's
like [WHOOSHING NOISE]..

01:17:45.220 --> 01:17:48.630
And many of the products that
people already came up with

01:17:48.630 --> 01:17:54.630
are like these kind of
linear, flat schedules.

01:17:54.630 --> 01:17:57.900
This has more wiggles, and
it's more non-linear than that.

01:17:57.900 --> 01:17:59.650
But this is all
negative territory.

01:17:59.650 --> 01:18:02.470
This is basically
ex-post premia down here.

01:18:02.470 --> 01:18:03.270
Yes.

01:18:03.270 --> 01:18:05.590
AUDIENCE: So these
[INAUDIBLE] models,

01:18:05.590 --> 01:18:08.390
do they try to account for
price changes that also result

01:18:08.390 --> 01:18:10.360
from aggregate weather shocks?

01:18:10.360 --> 01:18:10.860
[INAUDIBLE]

01:18:10.860 --> 01:18:10.980
ROBERT TOWNSEND: No.

01:18:10.980 --> 01:18:13.322
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
everybody [INAUDIBLE]..

01:18:13.322 --> 01:18:15.530
Because that could push it
in the opposite direction.

01:18:15.530 --> 01:18:18.590
AUDIENCE: Yes, absolutely.

01:18:18.590 --> 01:18:21.160
And I couldn't agree more.

01:18:21.160 --> 01:18:23.660
Now, at some level, you've
got to either use data

01:18:23.660 --> 01:18:26.840
to decide how price is moving--

01:18:26.840 --> 01:18:28.690
that's a good starting point--

01:18:28.690 --> 01:18:33.230
and/or incorporate in your
model like we saw with the macro

01:18:33.230 --> 01:18:34.880
development models,
the movements

01:18:34.880 --> 01:18:39.270
of wages and interest rates
and so on with interventions.

01:18:39.270 --> 01:18:44.280
So you don't have to
do just one thing,

01:18:44.280 --> 01:18:47.400
but you're right-- you need
to take it into account.

01:18:47.400 --> 01:18:50.592
In Thailand, rice is
the dominant crop.

01:18:50.592 --> 01:18:52.800
It's pretty hard to argue
that like the price of rice

01:18:52.800 --> 01:18:54.960
in the village is a
function of village or even

01:18:54.960 --> 01:18:56.475
necessarily regional rainfall.

01:19:00.595 --> 01:19:02.762
AUDIENCE: It would have to
be a pretty big aggregate

01:19:02.762 --> 01:19:03.873
[INAUDIBLE] price.

01:19:03.873 --> 01:19:04.790
ROBERT TOWNSEND: Yeah.

01:19:09.530 --> 01:19:16.730
So we want to do something
like that, that optimal design,

01:19:16.730 --> 01:19:18.500
to take into account
what we've learned

01:19:18.500 --> 01:19:22.190
about within-village insurance,
and their heterogeneity,

01:19:22.190 --> 01:19:24.230
and so on.

01:19:24.230 --> 01:19:27.770
Just two comments--
first of all,

01:19:27.770 --> 01:19:30.310
is it true that
within-village stuff is great

01:19:30.310 --> 01:19:33.830
and across-village stuff is not?

01:19:33.830 --> 01:19:36.470
Well, in Thailand it's
not obvious at all.

01:19:36.470 --> 01:19:38.180
And in Hong's helped with this.

01:19:38.180 --> 01:19:40.250
We updated some earlier results.

01:19:40.250 --> 01:19:43.190
But basically this
section of the slides,

01:19:43.190 --> 01:19:45.770
which I won't
attempt to go over,

01:19:45.770 --> 01:19:49.920
is how to test not only within
villages but across villages.

01:19:49.920 --> 01:19:55.040
And then you can aggregate
it up, villages, and test

01:19:55.040 --> 01:19:57.480
one county versus another.

01:19:57.480 --> 01:20:01.940
So you have you have layered
sort of degrees of aggregation.

01:20:01.940 --> 01:20:07.610
And you can use [INAUDIBLE]
method-- she did it in Kenya--

01:20:07.610 --> 01:20:11.120
to see how good the insurance
is across the villages.

01:20:11.120 --> 01:20:15.260
And in Thailand it's hard to
say that it's worse than what's

01:20:15.260 --> 01:20:17.660
going on within the village.

01:20:17.660 --> 01:20:21.260
So it's just
massive remittances.

01:20:21.260 --> 01:20:25.160
There's just huge
financial flows coming in,

01:20:25.160 --> 01:20:28.400
which we pick up in
the transactions data.

01:20:28.400 --> 01:20:37.520
So I still have misgivings
about pushing too hard on this.

01:20:37.520 --> 01:20:39.690
I'm sort of torn.

01:20:39.690 --> 01:20:43.350
I'm torn by the attractiveness
of designing the intervention

01:20:43.350 --> 01:20:46.680
based on the data, and yet
worried that they really don't

01:20:46.680 --> 01:20:48.900
need this rainfall product.

01:20:48.900 --> 01:20:55.910
And the other thing I want
to just point to so you can--

01:20:55.910 --> 01:20:58.790
sorry, Hong, all your
great stuff here--

01:21:02.720 --> 01:21:06.440
is to say that Chris Udry,
with Dean and co-authors,

01:21:06.440 --> 01:21:12.800
have been doing stuff
in Ghana, and they

01:21:12.800 --> 01:21:14.180
have various treatments.

01:21:14.180 --> 01:21:16.940
They have rainfall insurance.

01:21:16.940 --> 01:21:19.210
They have credit.

01:21:19.210 --> 01:21:20.270
They have both.

01:21:20.270 --> 01:21:21.610
They have one and the other.

01:21:21.610 --> 01:21:23.530
They have controls.

01:21:23.530 --> 01:21:26.110
And then you see stuff.

01:21:26.110 --> 01:21:28.300
Like you see
sometimes that credit

01:21:28.300 --> 01:21:30.760
seems to increase investment.

01:21:30.760 --> 01:21:36.610
But you also see that the
combination of insurance

01:21:36.610 --> 01:21:42.300
and credit is actually not
helping, although insurance

01:21:42.300 --> 01:21:44.640
alone actually can help.

01:21:44.640 --> 01:21:49.380
So they wrote down a model,
a simple two-period model,

01:21:49.380 --> 01:21:52.380
which is clear about the
optimization problem.

01:21:52.380 --> 01:21:54.120
And it's similar
in spirit to what

01:21:54.120 --> 01:21:56.100
we're talking about
today, which is what's

01:21:56.100 --> 01:21:59.160
the shadow price of current
consumption, what's the shadow

01:21:59.160 --> 01:22:01.170
price of future consumption.

01:22:01.170 --> 01:22:03.540
If there is full insurance--
which they assume

01:22:03.540 --> 01:22:04.722
in the village--

01:22:04.722 --> 01:22:06.180
and there are no
aggregate shocks--

01:22:06.180 --> 01:22:08.360
which they assume in the model--

01:22:08.360 --> 01:22:13.590
then basically you can get
counterintuitive effects going

01:22:13.590 --> 01:22:17.670
on when you offer insurance.

01:22:17.670 --> 01:22:19.530
Because insurance
moves tomorrow, it

01:22:19.530 --> 01:22:22.080
makes tomorrow kind of less
valuable in some sense.

01:22:22.080 --> 01:22:25.410
It actually seems to
undercut investment today.

01:22:25.410 --> 01:22:31.020
And these other papers are again
treatments, RCTs and so on.

01:22:33.840 --> 01:22:38.570
It's easy to get lost in
the details of these things,

01:22:38.570 --> 01:22:41.510
and get caught up with
the language of take-up,

01:22:41.510 --> 01:22:46.010
and behavioral responses, and
some very real things that

01:22:46.010 --> 01:22:47.480
are out there.

01:22:47.480 --> 01:22:51.290
But it's important
not to get lost,

01:22:51.290 --> 01:22:54.290
and to remember the
basic sort of framework

01:22:54.290 --> 01:22:57.530
that you're taking
in if you choose

01:22:57.530 --> 01:23:03.010
to design one of these
randomized control trials.

01:23:03.010 --> 01:23:05.030
Or let me put it another way.

01:23:05.030 --> 01:23:09.380
If Udry had not been thinking
about those kinds of models,

01:23:09.380 --> 01:23:12.440
he would be left with some
very strange puzzles that

01:23:12.440 --> 01:23:14.670
does beg for an interpretation.

01:23:14.670 --> 01:23:16.280
But even better
yet, when you have

01:23:16.280 --> 01:23:19.610
the model and the structure,
ideally, with enough data,

01:23:19.610 --> 01:23:21.740
you can actually
design interventions

01:23:21.740 --> 01:23:25.730
which are informative about
key parameters in the model

01:23:25.730 --> 01:23:30.520
and your guesses
about basic obstacles.